### Compute the percentage increase in sales.

The percentage increase in sales will be used in calculating the required increase in assets.

The formula is as follows.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Percentage Increase in Sales}&= \dfrac{\text{Increase in Sales}}{\text{Current Sales}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the percentage increase in sales is calculated as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Percentage Increase in Sales}&= \dfrac{\text{Increase in Sales}}{\text{Current Sales}}\\[15pt]

&= \dfrac{\$75,000.00}{\$715,000.00}\\[15pt]

&= 0.1049 \times 100 \\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{10.49\%}}

\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the percentage increase in sales is **$10.49%**.

### Compute the required increase in assets.

Assets are proportion to the projected increase in sales. Whenever there is a projected increase in sales, the assets should be adjusted in proportion to the increase since the assumption is that assets are working at total capacity.

The formula and calculation are as follows.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Increase in Asset}&= \text{Percentage Increase in Sales} \times \text{Assets}\\[15pt]

&= 10.49\% \times \$520,000.00\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{\$54,548.00}}
\end{aligned}
$$
